name: Sugar (white, brown)
sources: Harvard Nutrition Source, Stanford Med, PubMed, BMJ
notes: Higher-risk ingredient when used frequently, especially in drinks

name: High-fructose corn syrup
sources: Princeton Research, Healthline, PubMed, Frontiers in Nutrition
notes: High-concern sweetener, comparable to or slightly worse than table sugar

name: Honey
sources: Nature, Cardiometabolic Health, Healthline, Mayo Clinic, PubMed
notes: Less concerning than refined sugar when used in small amounts as substitute

name: Maple syrup
sources: Canadian Maple, Diabetes Care Community, Indiana Maple Syrup, PubMed
notes: Somewhat more favorable than table sugar due to lower GI and polyphenols

name: Agave nectar
sources: Healthline, WebMD, Medical News Today, PubMed
notes: Low GI but very high fructose creates long-term metabolic risk

name: Molasses
sources: Healthline, Dr. Axe, Taylor & Francis, PubMed, ScienceDirect
notes: Nutrient-dense with gentler post-meal responses than refined sugar

name: Stevia
notes: Well-tolerated within ADI limits, favorable for sugar replacement

name: Erythritol
sources: PubMed, Health.com, Cleveland Clinic, WebMD, Nutrition Facts
notes: Very low blood sugar impact; caution flag around cardiovascular association

name: Xylitol
sources: Healthline, PubMed, Sage Journals, VeryWell Health
notes: Dental benefits but significant GI downside; toxic to dogs

name: Maltose
sources: MedicineNet, Blue Circle, Dr. Axe, Healthline, PubMed

name: Dextrose
sources: PubMed, Glycemic Index, WebMD, Cleveland Clinic, Medical News Today
notes: Pure glucose, GI of 100, extremely spike-prone

name: Glucose syrup
sources: Glycemic Index, PubMed, Ragus, Healthline, Academic OUP

name: Fructose
sources: PubMed, Physiology.org, ScienceDirect, Glycemic Index, Penn Medicine
notes: Low GI but high liver/metabolic risk at high intakes

name: Invert sugar
sources: VeryWell Health, Fitelo, Vively, Oreate AI, Webstaurant Store
notes: Similar to or slightly worse than sucrose

name: Sorbitol
notes: Low GI but major gut tolerance issues, commonly causes bloating

name: Butter
sources: Ultrahuman, PubMed, Academic OUP, USU Extension, Joslin
notes: Won't spike blood sugar but saturated fat concerns for lipids

name: Margarine
sources: Harvard Nutrition Source, PubMed, Mayo Clinic, Eating Well
notes: Varies by formulation; modern versions better than historical trans-fat versions

name: Vegetable oil
sources: PubMed, Stanford Med, ScienceDirect, Nutrition.org, UC News
notes: Neutral blood sugar; omega-6 concerns with heavy use

name: Canola oil
sources: PubMed, Managed Healthcare Executive, Diabetes Journals, U of T
notes: Good MUFA/ALA profile, RCTs show glycemic benefits in T2D

name: Sunflower oil
sources: PubMed, Sugarfit, Zeroacre, BHF, Stanford Med, Health.com
notes: High omega-6 warrants moderation to avoid inflammation

name: Olive oil
sources: About Olive Oil, Nature, PubMed, BHOOC, Diabetes Journals
notes: Strong anti-inflammatory, excellent for metabolic health

name: Coconut oil
sources: PubMed, BMJ Open, ACC, JAMA Network, ScienceDirect

name: Palm oil
notes: Middle-of-the-road saturated fat; interesterified forms concerning

name: Shortening
sources: Harvard Nutrition Source, PubMed, Healthline, Lipid.org, Dr. Axe
notes: Historical trans-fat concerns; even newer versions not ideal

name: Lard
sources: General saturated fat research, PubMed cohorts
notes: Traditional animal fat; okay occasionally in balanced diet

name: Ghee
sources: PubMed, ScienceDirect, Cambridge Core, WebMD, Cleveland Clinic
notes: Concentrated dairy fat; context-dependent in traditional diets

name: Peanut oil
notes: Reasonably cardiometabolic-friendly when not for heavy frying

name: Soybean oil
sources: ScienceDirect, PubMed, PLOS ONE, UC Riverside News
notes: High PUFA but omega-6 heavy; animal data shows harm at high doses

name: Fish oil
sources: PubMed, WHO, Nutrition Insight, VeryWell Health, SciTech Daily
notes: Anti-inflammatory, lowers triglycerides; neutral on blood sugar

name: Avocado oil
sources: PubMed, Cleveland Clinic, Zoe, Healthline, ScienceDirect
notes: Olive-oil-like profile; good for metabolic health

name: Cow milk (whole)
notes: Complete protein, lactose may affect some

name: Goat milk
notes: Easier digestion for some, different fat structure

name: Sheep milk
notes: Higher fat and protein than cow milk

name: Heavy cream
notes: Very high fat, low carb, saturated fat concerns

name: Cheddar cheese
notes: High saturated fat, low carb, high sodium

name: Cream cheese
notes: High fat, used in small amounts

name: Almond milk (unsweetened)
notes: Very low calorie, fortified versions better

name: Collagen peptides
notes: Skin and joint benefits, incomplete protein

name: Edamame
notes: Whole soy, fiber and protein rich

name: Quinoa
notes: Complete plant protein, all amino acids

name: Poppy seeds
notes: Trace minerals, used in small amounts

name: Almond flour
notes: Very low carb, high fat, keto-friendly

name: Salt (sodium chloride)
notes: Essential but excess linked to hypertension

name: Sodium benzoate
notes: Antimicrobial, benzene concern with vitamin C

name: Caramel color
notes: Heated sugar, 4-MEI concerns in Class IV

name: Red 40 (Allura Red)
notes: Most common red dye, behavioral concerns debated

name: Watermelon
notes: Lycopene, high GI but low GL

name: Dates
notes: High fiber despite high sugar, minerals

name: Maltitol
notes: Higher GI than others, GI issues
